            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. The day she saw the housing protest outside City Hall for the first time, a wave of profound sadness and righteous anger washed over her. Seeing families holding signs about being priced out solidified the human cost of policy failures, fueling her resolve to work *within* the system and fight for tangible change, not just theoretical solutions. (Early in her Master's internship, around 2008)\n\n2. Trudging through Golden Gate Park one misty morning after a particularly grueling policy debate, a sense of quiet peace settled over her. The towering redwoods and damp earth reminded her of the enduring beauty and resilience of the city, grounding her and reaffirming her dedication to preserving its spirit, even amidst the challenges. (Regularly, ongoing throughout her time in SF)\n\n3. Hearing her affordable housing bill pass a crucial committee vote for the first time filled her with a mix of exhilaration and relief. It felt like a small but significant victory after countless hours of pushing, proving to herself that strategic persistence could indeed move the needle, strengthening her belief in the power of incremental progress. (Several years into her role as Senior Policy Advisor, around 2018)\n\n4. A long, honest conversation with a colleague after a demanding week, sharing their frustrations and small triumphs, forged a deep connection. It revealed the strength in shared purpose and the importance of building a supportive community within the demanding world of city policy, showing her the value of professional kinship. (Mid-career at the City and County, around 2015)\n\n5. Walking into a community meeting in a neighborhood struggling with housing insecurity and hearing a resident thank her, specifically, for a policy tweak she helped implement, brought tears to her eyes. It was a visceral reminder of the real-world impact of her work, solidifying her commitment to centering the voices of those most affected by her decisions. (Later in her role as Senior Policy Advisor, around 2020)"
